task_1.query_used: Search LinkedIn for current role and professional details of Ali Khaledi Nasab at Amazon
task_1.data:
Ali Khaledi Nasab is a physicist and AI scientist currently working at Amazon's Rufus division. Originally from Iran, he moved to the United States in 2014 to pursue his Ph.D. After completing his doctorate, he joined Stanford University's Department of Neurosurgery, focusing on developing stimulation methods for treating neurological disorders. In 2021, he transitioned to CODA Biotherapeutics, a gene therapy startup targeting epilepsy treatments. Following the startup's closure in 2022 due to funding challenges, he joined Amazon as a research scientist in the AWS network capacity team. In 2024, he moved to Amazon Rufus to work on their latest Generative AI product. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

Throughout his career, Dr. Khaledi Nasab has contributed to various research projects, including studying the dynamics of excitable tree networks in sensory neurons and exploring methods to depolarize echo chambers in social networks. He has also been involved in editing the Brain Development section of the "Encyclopedia of Child and Adolescent Health," which received the 2024 PROSE Award for significant contributions in Clinical Medicine. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

In addition to his professional work, Dr. Khaledi Nasab has shared insights on career development, such as offering advice on successful job interviews. ([ali-khaledi1989.medium.com](https://ali-khaledi1989.medium.com/an-introduction-to-a-successful-job-interview-b4925c49d98?utm_source=openai))

task_2.query_used: Check Google Scholar for academic publications or research papers by Ali Khaledi Nasab in AI and Machine Learning
task_2.data:
Ali Khaledi-Nasab is a researcher affiliated with Amazon, specializing in machine learning, artificial intelligence, networks, computational neuroscience, and nonlinear dynamics. ([scholar.google.com](https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=Ash32BAAAAAJ&utm_source=openai))

His academic contributions include a 2016 study titled "Potato extract as reducing agent and stabiliser in a facile green one-step synthesis of ZnO nanoparticles," which has been cited 129 times. ([scholar.google.com](https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=Ash32BAAAAAJ&utm_source=openai))

Another notable work is "Size-dependent intersubband optical properties of dome-shaped InAs/GaAs quantum dots with wetting layer," published in 2012, with 97 citations. ([scholar.google.com](https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=Ash32BAAAAAJ&utm_source=openai))

Additionally, Khaledi-Nasab co-authored a 2024 mini-review titled "A mini review on the applications of artificial intelligence (AI) in surface chemistry and catalysis," highlighting the integration of AI in these fields. ([degruyter.com](https://www.degruyter.com/document/doi/10.1515/tsd-2024-2580/html?lang=en&srsltid=AfmBOoq2Ah3RoDgAuDZLTwpWZGyKtcKJNZUhqKCdNDrzAC3arLHpsBIC&utm_source=openai))

These publications reflect his interdisciplinary research interests and contributions to advancing AI and machine learning applications.

task_3.query_used: Search Iranian and US university alumni databases for educational background
task_3.data:
Ali Khaledi Nasab is a graduate student in Physics & Astronomy at Ohio University. He has been involved in research on the dynamics of excitable tree networks, particularly in sensory neurons with tree-like structures. In October 2017, he delivered a colloquium talk at the College of Wooster titled "Emergent stochastic oscillations and signal detection in tree networks of excitable elements." His research advisor is Dr. Alexander Neiman, a Professor of Physics & Astronomy at Ohio University. ([ohio-forum.com](https://www.ohio-forum.com/2017/10/khaledi-nasab-gives-colloquium-talk-college-wooster/?utm_source=openai)) In May 2019, Khaledi Nasab received an American Physical Society (APS) Division of Biological Physics 2019 Student Travel Award, which supported his attendance at the annual APS meeting in Boston, where he presented his paper on the dynamics of excitable tree networks. ([ohio-forum.com](https://www.ohio-forum.com/2019/05/khaledi-nasab-receives-aps-travel-award-to-attend-conference/?utm_source=openai))

Regarding his educational background, specific details about his undergraduate studies are not readily available in the provided sources. However, his current research and academic activities suggest a strong foundation in physics and neuroscience.

task_4.query_used: Review Amazon.com research team pages and publications for professional affiliations
task_4.data:
Dr. Ali Khaledi-Nasab is a physicist and AI scientist currently serving as a Principal Research Scientist in Product Knowledge at Amazon. He joined Amazon in October 2022, initially working as a research scientist in the AWS network capacity team before transitioning to Amazon Rufus in 2024 to focus on generative AI products. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

Prior to his tenure at Amazon, Dr. Khaledi-Nasab held several notable positions:

- **Stanford University School of Medicine**: He worked in the Department of Neurosurgery, collaborating with Dr. Peter Tass on developing stimulation methods for treating neurological disorders, including Parkinson's disease. ([med.stanford.edu](https://med.stanford.edu/tass-lab/publications.html?utm_source=openai))

- **CODA Biotherapeutics**: As a senior researcher, he focused on designing chemogenetic approaches for treating neurological disorders such as epilepsy and pain. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

In addition to his professional roles, Dr. Khaledi-Nasab has contributed to academia as an adjunct professor of physics at Ohio University. He also served as the editor for the Brain Development section of the "Encyclopedia of Child and Adolescent Health," a project that received the 2024 PROSE Award for "significant contributions" in Clinical Medicine. ([alikhaledi.com](https://www.alikhaledi.com/?utm_source=openai))

His research interests encompass machine learning, artificial intelligence, networks, and computational neuroscience. He has an extensive publication record, with works featured in journals such as *Scientific Reports* and *Frontiers in Network Physiology*. ([scholar.google.com](https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=Ash32BAAAAAJ&utm_source=openai))

task_5.query_used: Search news archives and tech publications for mentions of Ali Khaledi Nasab's AI research work
task_5.data:
Ali Khaledi Nasab has contributed significantly to the field of AI, particularly in understanding the dynamics of excitable tree networks in sensory neurons. His research focuses on the stochastic behavior and signal detection mechanisms within these networks, which are crucial for sensory processing in organisms. For instance, in 2017, he presented a colloquium at the College of Wooster titled "Emergent stochastic oscillations and signal detection in tree networks of excitable elements," where he discussed how spontaneous activity in these networks can be predicted by analyzing a single effective node with scaled parameters. ([ohio-forum.com](https://www.ohio-forum.com/2017/10/khaledi-nasab-gives-colloquium-talk-college-wooster/?utm_source=openai))

In 2019, Khaledi Nasab received the American Physical Society's Division of Biological Physics Student Travel Award, enabling him to present his paper, "Dynamics of excitable tree networks: Application to sensory neurons," at the annual APS meeting in Boston. His research delves into the dynamical principles of functioning and information processing in sensory neurons with tree-like structures, such as those found in muscle spindles and mechanoreceptors. ([ohio-forum.com](https://www.ohio-forum.com/2019/05/khaledi-nasab-receives-aps-travel-award-to-attend-conference/?utm_source=openai))

Additionally, Khaledi Nasab has been involved in discussions on the challenges faced by international students in the U.S., particularly in light of travel bans. In 2017, he authored an article in *Science* magazine titled "Standing up to fear," where he shared his personal experiences and the broader implications of such policies on the international academic community. ([academia.edu](https://www.academia.edu/32689067/Standing_up_to_fear?utm_source=openai))

These contributions highlight Khaledi Nasab's interdisciplinary approach, bridging physics, neuroscience, and social issues, and underscore his commitment to advancing our understanding of complex systems and advocating for the rights of international scholars.
